        title: "CLAIMS",
        content: "1. A computer-implemented method for secondary infertility prevention during postpartum recovery comprising: continuously monitoring physiological data from at least one wearable device worn by a postpartum user; identifying emerging risk factors for secondary infertility from the monitored data across five categories comprising thyroid function indicators from basal body temperature pattern analysis, hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis recovery from menstrual cycle quality assessment, metabolic recovery from glucose regulation patterns, nutritional status from proxy indicator analysis, and stress response normalization from heart rate variability trajectory; deploying proactive AI-driven interventions targeting identified risk factors through nutritional optimization, supplement protocol adjustment, and lifestyle recommendations during the postpartum recovery period; generating a fertility readiness assessment distinct from the postpartum recovery score, evaluating the user's physiological state against fertility optimization criteria including luteal phase adequacy, cycle regularity, ovulation quality, metabolic readiness, and nutritional readiness; and managing transition from postpartum recovery experience to fertility optimization experience upon user intent confirmation when the fertility readiness assessment indicates physiological optimization, with complete preservation of all pre-pregnancy, pregnancy, and postpartum physiological data.\n\n2. The method of claim 1, wherein identifying thyroid function risk factors comprises detecting persistently low follicular phase basal body temperatures, reduced temperature amplitude between follicular and luteal phases, and temperature pattern instability from continuous wearable monitoring data, and triggering thyroid panel testing recommendations through a clinical bridge system when risk indicators exceed threshold for three or more consecutive post-delivery cycles.\n\n3. The method of claim 1, wherein the fertility readiness assessment distinguishes between cycle-resumed-but-not-optimized states characterized by resumed menstruation with inadequate luteal phases, anovulatory cycles, or irregular timing, and fertility-ready states characterized by adequate luteal phase length, consistent ovulation quality, metabolic stability, and nutritional repletion.\n\n4. The method of claim 1, wherein the fertility readiness score is maintained internally without display to the user during the postpartum period to avoid creating pressure around future conception timing, and is used to determine when to offer transition from postpartum to fertility optimization experience.\n\n5. A secondary infertility prevention system comprising: a risk factor identification module configured to monitor five categories of secondary infertility risk factors from continuous wearable data and self-reported inputs during postpartum recovery; an intervention deployment module configured to activate nutritional, supplement, and lifestyle interventions targeting identified risk factors during the recovery window when intervention is most effective; a fertility readiness assessment engine configured to evaluate physiological state against fertility optimization criteria independently from postpartum recovery scoring; and a transition management module configured to facilitate seamless transition from postpartum to fertility optimization experience with complete data continuity upon user intent confirmation."
