        content: "Perimenopause, the transition to menopause characterized by declining ovarian function and fluctuating hormone levels, affects every woman and typically begins between ages thirty-five and fifty-five, lasting four to ten years before final menstrual period. Current clinical detection relies on the STRAW+10 staging system, which defines early perimenopause through persistent variability of seven or more days in consecutive cycle lengths. However, this clinical definition requires that cycle irregularity has already become established and persistent, meaning detection occurs only after the transition is well underway.\n\nExisting consumer health applications addressing perimenopause are symptom trackers that record hot flashes, night sweats, mood changes, and cycle irregularity after they occur. These applications provide documentation of the transition experience but offer no predictive capability. By the time symptoms are sufficiently distressing to prompt tracking, the perimenopause transition may have been progressing at the physiological level for months or years.\n\nClinical laboratory testing for perimenopause typically involves measuring follicle-stimulating hormone levels, but FSH fluctuates significantly during early perimenopause and a single measurement provides limited diagnostic value. Serial FSH testing is not standard clinical practice due to cost and the inherent variability of results.\n\nThe gap between the onset of physiological changes associated with perimenopause and clinical recognition of the transition represents a critical intervention opportunity. Early detection would enable proactive management of symptoms before they become distressing, nutritional and lifestyle interventions during the window of maximum effectiveness, informed decision-making about hormone replacement therapy before symptom severity drives reactive treatment decisions, and psychological preparation for a life transition that many women experience as unexpected and distressing.\n\nWhat is needed is a system that can detect the earliest physiological indicators of perimenopause through continuous wearable monitoring, leveraging personal historical baselines to identify changes that would be invisible using population-level reference ranges."
