        content: "The GI-hormonal correlation engine comprises four analytical modules: a food-GI correlation module, a phase-timing analysis module, a nutritional intervention engine, and a longitudinal pattern learning module.\n\nFood-GI Correlation Module\n\nThe food-GI correlation module analyzes temporal relationships between dietary inputs and GI symptom reports. Users log meals through the nutrition tracking interface, recording food types, preparation methods, portion sizes, and timing. GI symptoms including bloating, gas, constipation, diarrhea, nausea, abdominal discomfort, and heartburn are tracked through brief check-ins at configurable intervals.\n\nThe correlation algorithm applies time-windowed analysis to identify foods that consistently precede GI symptoms within zero to twenty-four hours. Statistical significance is calculated across multiple occurrences, with a minimum threshold of three food-symptom co-occurrences required before a correlation is flagged. The system accounts for confounders including stress events, sleep quality, and concurrent medication use.\n\nCritically, the food-GI correlation is analyzed within the context of cycle phase. A food that consistently triggers bloating during the luteal phase but not during the follicular phase represents a phase-specific sensitivity that would be missed by non-cycle-aware analysis. This phase-specific food sensitivity mapping is the primary novel contribution of the food-GI correlation module.\n\nPhase-Timing Analysis Module\n\nThe phase-timing module maps GI symptom patterns to cycle phases and hormonal transition stages. For each GI symptom category, the system calculates phase-specific prevalence rates: the percentage of follicular phase days, ovulatory days, luteal phase days, and menstrual days on which each symptom is reported. Significant phase-specific clustering, defined as symptom prevalence in one phase exceeding two times the prevalence in other phases, is flagged as a phase-dependent GI pattern.\n\nAs the perimenopause transition progresses, the system tracks changes in these phase-specific patterns. Early perimenopause may show emerging luteal-phase GI sensitivity that was not present in prior years. Mid-perimenopause may show increasingly variable GI patterns correlating with increasing hormonal variability. Late perimenopause may show chronic GI changes that are no longer phase-dependent but persistent.\n\nThe phase-timing module also integrates data from the perimenopause detection system to correlate GI pattern changes with specific hormonal transition indicators. This enables the system to identify when GI changes are occurring as part of the hormonal transition versus when they represent independent GI pathology requiring clinical evaluation.\n\nNutritional Intervention Engine\n\nBased on identified correlations and phase-timing patterns, the AI nutrition agent automatically deploys targeted nutritional interventions. These interventions fall into five categories.\n\nPhase-specific food avoidance: When specific foods trigger GI symptoms only during certain cycle phases, the nutrition agent adjusts meal suggestions to avoid or reduce those foods during sensitive phases while maintaining them during non-sensitive phases. This preserves dietary variety while minimizing GI distress.\n\nGut-supporting nutrition optimization: The system increases emphasis on gut-supporting nutrients during phases of heightened GI sensitivity, including prebiotic fiber from specific food sources, probiotic-rich foods, anti-inflammatory foods including omega-three fatty acids and turmeric, and foods supporting bile acid metabolism including bitter greens and artichoke.\n\nMeal timing and composition adjustment: The system adjusts meal timing, portion sizes, and macronutrient composition based on identified patterns. For example, if evening meals consistently trigger overnight GI distress during the luteal phase, the system suggests earlier dinner timing and modified evening meal composition.\n\nHydration and fiber optimization: The system tracks hydration intake and fiber consumption, adjusting recommendations based on GI symptom patterns. Constipation-predominant phases receive increased hydration and soluble fiber emphasis. Diarrhea-predominant phases receive adjusted fiber type recommendations.\n\nPhytoestrogen strategic deployment: During phases of heightened estrogen-related GI disruption, the system strategically increases phytoestrogen-containing foods including soy, flax, and legumes to partially compensate for declining endogenous estrogen effects on gut function.\n\nLongitudinal Pattern Learning Module\n\nThe system maintains a longitudinal database of food-GI correlations, phase-timing patterns, and intervention outcomes across the user's entire perimenopause transition. As the transition progresses and new patterns emerge, the system continuously updates its intervention strategies. Interventions that successfully reduce GI symptoms in specific contexts are reinforced. Interventions that fail to produce improvement are retired and alternatives deployed."
